<subsection xml:id="subsubsec-area-of-parallelograms" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Area of Parallelograms</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.5 Area of Polygons
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Determine the area of quadrilaterals in different situations. Explore the area of polygons as used in real-life situations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define a parallelogram as a quadrilateral whose opposite sides are equal and parallel. State the area formula: <m>\text{Area} = \text{base} \times \text{height}</m>, where the height is the perpendicular distance between parallel sides. Recognise that the area formula is the same as for a rectangle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the area of parallelograms using the formula. Find the perpendicular height using trigonometry when given the slant side and angle. Find missing dimensions given the area.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving areas of parallelograms (floors, billboards, solar panels). Apply trigonometric relationships to find perpendicular heights in parallelograms.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/area-of-parallelograms.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/step-by-step-guide_area-of-parallelograms.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Exploring the Area of a Parallelogram</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Groups of 2–3 students
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Setup</title>
                <p>
                    Distribute graph paper, scissors, rulers, coloured pencils, and parallelogram templates. Students will draw, cut, and rearrange a parallelogram to discover the area formula.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Circulate among groups, ensuring students understand how to drop a perpendicular correctly.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Ask probing questions: <q>What shape do you get when you rearrange the parallelogram?</q>, <q>How does the area of the parallelogram compare to the area of the rectangle?</q>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                For struggling groups: <q>Let us draw the perpendicular together. It must be at a right angle to the base.</q>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                For early finishers: <q>Can you find a formula for the area of a parallelogram?</q>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Guide students to articulate: <q>The area of a parallelogram is base × height, just like a rectangle.</q>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Identify 2–3 groups with clear calculations to share with the class.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>


        <activity xml:id="auto_s3w6ks72">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_d29x29rv">
                <m> \textbf{Exploring the Area of a parallelogram}.</m>
            </p>
        
            <p xml:id="auto_7i1hckqw">
            Materials needed.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hz5hqe44">
                <ul xml:id="auto_sikez093">
                    <li xml:id="auto_sf8wmb0v">
                        <p xml:id="auto_0o6g3fxm">
                            Graph paper
                        </p>

                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ib8r0ww0">
                        <p xml:id="auto_p979g1gi">
                            Scissors
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_64ow017q">
                        <p xml:id="auto_a57mj29e">
                            Ruler
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_sudo7fbv">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ag211bz8">
                            Colored pencils
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_2xz3iu7s">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ls98bkla">
                            A printed or drawn parallelogram template.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p> 
                
                <p xml:id="auto_4ljwfkj0">
                    Steps for the activity.
                </p> 
                <sidebyside> 
                    <p xml:id="auto_lp15od7b">
                <ol xml:id="auto_97adsuc0">
                    <li xml:id="auto_fzuoywfc">   
                        <p xml:id="auto_rncsj9gj">
                            Draw a parallelogram.
                            <ol xml:id="auto_fflpkeic">
                                <li xml:id="auto_lh7vhhxj">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_4imhchnu">
                                        On graph paper, draw a parallelogram with  a given base and height.  Label the vertices A, B, C and D. 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_ksoticdq">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_f6uzk3mk">
                                        Use a pair of campus to drop a perpendicular. Lable the intersection point on line CD as H representing the height of the parallelogram.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_76rl94ab">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_8gc76nde">
                                        Use a  ruler to measure and compare opposite sides (AB and CD, BC and AD. ) 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>  
                </p>
                
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="parallelogram-three-one">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Define the parallelogram vertices
                        \coordinate (A) at (-2,1);
                        \coordinate (B) at (2,1);
                        \coordinate (C) at (3,-1);
                        \coordinate (D) at (-1,-1);
                        % Draw the parallelogram with thick pink outline
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Draw perpendicular height from B to base C-D
                        \coordinate (H) at (2,-1); % Foot of the perpendicular from B to CD
                        \draw[dotted, thick] (B) -- (H);
                        
                        % Mark the right angle with a visible square towards the right of H
                        \draw[thick] (H) ++(0,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0) -- ++(0,-0.3) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Label the vertices
                        \node[above left] at (A) {A};
                        \node[above right] at (B) {B};
                        \node[below right] at (C) {C};
                        \node[below left] at (D) {D};
                        \node[below] at (H) {H};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </sidebyside>
            
        </statement>
    </activity>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the area formula for parallelograms: <m>\text{Area} = \text{base} \times \text{height}</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Scaffolding Strategies</title>
            <p>
                Address common misconceptions:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I can use the slant side as the height.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> The height must be the perpendicular distance between parallel sides.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>The area formula is different from a rectangle.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> The formula is the same: base × height.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I need to know all four sides to find the area.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> You only need the base and the perpendicular height.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>The height is always vertical.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> The height is perpendicular to the base, which can be horizontal or at an angle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
    <insight>
        <p xml:id="auto_t1v1otw2">
            A parallelogram is a quadrilateral whose opposite sides are equal and parallel. Which other quadrilateral has similar characteristics like these?
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_nibyl42l">
            🔹 The area of a parallelogram is given by: <m>Base \times Height</m>:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_pdyfvqz6">
            <md>
                <mrow>\text{A } = \amp \, b \times h </mrow> 
            </md>
            where <m>b</m>  is the base and  <m>h </m> the perpendicular distance between the given pair of parallel sides.
        </p>
        <p>
            Make sure you use the perpendicular height <m>h</m>, not the slanted edge of the parallelogram.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Students apply the parallelogram area formula through worked examples, including using trigonometry to find the height.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Work through the first example on the board, modelling how to use the sine function to find the perpendicular height when given the slant side and angle. Then direct students to attempt the second example independently. Circulate to support learners who struggle with the trigonometric step.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    
    <example xml:id="auto_ojsgs3p3">
        <statement>
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_fqvtva5q">
                    <ul xml:id="auto_n1ymx09h">
                    <li xml:id="auto_63cgiy04">
                <p xml:id="auto_lyp3xd7f">
                    A parallelogram  PQRS is of sides 28cm and 7cm. 
                        If <m>\angle</m> QRS is <m>75^\circ</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_sczhyiat">
                    a. Find the height the parallelogram using sine rule.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ftzh5bpp">
                    b. Find the area of the parallelogram.
                </p>
                    </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="parallelogram-one">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Define the parallelogram vertices
                        \coordinate (A) at (-2,1);
                        \coordinate (B) at (2,1);
                        \coordinate (C) at (3,-1);
                        \coordinate (D) at (-1,-1);
                            % Draw the parallelogram with thick pink outline
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Draw perpendicular height from B to base C-D
                        \coordinate (H) at (2,-1); % Foot of the perpendicular from B to CD
                        \draw[dotted, thick] (B) -- (H);
                        
                        % Mark the right angle with a visible square towards the right of H
                        \draw[thick] (H) ++(0,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0) -- ++(0,-0.3) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Label the vertices
                        \node[above left] at (A) {P};
                        \node[above right] at (B) {Q};
                        \node[below right] at (C) {R};
                        \node[below left] at (D) {S};
                        \node[below] at (H) {T};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </sidebyside>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_omjt25p7">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_t4ptjugt">
                From Q drop a perpendicular to meet RS at T considering <m>\angle QRS</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ajsrw6vu">
                <m>\text{Height (QT)} = \text{Hypotenuse(BC)} \times \text{sin} \theta</m>
                <md>
                    <mrow> QT =  \amp 7 \, \text{sin} 75^\circ </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 6.76  \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3sncvul8">
                b. 
                <md>
                        
                    <mrow> \text{Area of PQRS} = \amp  RS \times PT </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 28 \times 7 \, \text{sin}  \, 75^\circ </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 189.32 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_g499f9wk">
                The area of the parallelogram is <m>189.32 \, \text{cm}^2.</m>
                </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A parallelogram <m>\mathbf{ABCD}</m> has sides <m>18\; cm</m> and <m>12 \;cm</m>. Given that <m>\angle \mathbf{BAD} = 38^\circ</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the height of the parallelogram relative to base <m>\mathbf{AB}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the area of the parallelogram.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the area if side <m>\mathbf{AD}</m> is taken as the base instead.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Drop a perpendicular from point <m>\mathbf{D}</m> to meet <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> at point <m>\mathbf{E}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            In right triangle <m>\mathbf{ADE}</m>:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Height<m>=\mathbf{AD\;sin\;(\angle BAD)}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\mathbf{DE} = 12 \times sin \;38^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\mathbf{DE} = 7.39 \; cm</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>
                                \text{Area} =  \text{Base} \times \text{Height}
                            </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m> \text{Area} = 18 \times 7.39 = 133.02\; cm^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Now the height relative to base AD comes from side AB
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Height <m>=</m> <m>AB \; sin \;38^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           Height <m>= 11.08 \; cm</m>  
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Area <m>= 12 \times 11.08 = 132.96 \; cm^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify common misconceptions.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
    <p xml:id="auto_ea0ptm60">
            Find the area of the parallelogram given below.
            </p>  
            <image width="60%">
            <latex-image label="parallelogram-example-one">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (5,3) -- (1,3) -- cycle;
                    \draw[dashed] (1,3) -- (1,0);
                    \node[below] at (2,0) {4 cm};
                    \node[left] at (0.3,1.5) {3 cm};
                \end{tikzpicture}

        
        </latex-image>
        </image>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                Area <m>= 4 \times 3 = 12 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
            </p>
        </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_rgw6kt4k">
                    Find the missing height of the parallelogram ABCD given the area is 24 cm² and base is 6 cm.
                </p>
                        <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="parallelogram-ten">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Define the parallelogram vertices
                        \coordinate (A) at (-2,1);
                        \coordinate (B) at (2,1);
                        \coordinate (C) at (3,-1);
                        \coordinate (D) at (-1,-1);
                            % Draw the parallelogram with thick pink outline
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Draw perpendicular height from B to base C-D
                        \coordinate (H) at (2,-1); % Foot of the perpendicular from B to CD
                        \draw[dotted, thick] (B) -- (H);
                        
                        % Mark the right angle with a visible square towards the right of H
                        \draw[thick] (H) ++(0,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0) -- ++(0,-0.3) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Label the vertices
                        \node[above left] at (A) {A};
                        \node[above right] at (B) {B};
                        \node[below right] at (C) {C};
                        \node[below left] at (D) {D};
                        \node[below] at (H) {H};
                        \node at (0.2,0) {A = $24\, cm^2$};
                        \node[below] at ($(D)!0.5!(C)$) {6 cm};

                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            Height <m>= \text{Area} \div \text{base} = 24 \div 6 = 4 \, \text{cm}</m>.
        </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
       <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_fz9au3nx">
                A construction company is building a parallelogram-shaped floor with a base of 10 meters and height of 6 meters. Find the area of the floor.

            </p>
       </statement> 
       <solution>
        <p>
            Area <m>= 10 \times 6 = 60 \, \text{m}^2</m>.
        </p>
       </solution>
    </exercise>
            
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_jr0k1lw6">
                A billboard has a parallelogram shape with a base of 12 feet and a height of 5 feet. Find the area of the billboard.

            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p> Area <m>= 12 \times 5 = 60 \, \text{ft}^2</m> </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>
            
            
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_4jrmgpd2">
                A solar panel is shaped like a parallelogram with a base of 8 meters and an inclined height of 4 meters. Find its surface area.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Area <m>= 8 \times 4 = 32 \, \text{m}^2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>
</exercises>
            
            
            
            

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide pre-drawn parallelograms with labels to help students visualise the problem. Use simpler numbers for base and height. Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers. Provide step-by-step calculation templates. Allow use of calculators.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Encourage students to draw their own diagrams from word problems. Ask students to explain which formula they chose and why. Provide mixed practice with both direct calculation and finding missing dimensions.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Challenge students to derive the formula themselves using the cut-and-rearrange method. Explore real-world applications: architecture, construction, engineering. Investigate the relationship between the area of a parallelogram and the area of a triangle. Apply the formula to find missing angles or sides when area is known.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Extension Activity: Designing Parallelogram-Shaped Structures</title>
            <p>
                Students work in groups to design a parallelogram-shaped structure (floor, billboard, solar panel) and calculate its area. They draw the structure on graph paper with appropriate dimensions, measure the base and height, and calculate the area. If the perpendicular height is not given, they use trigonometry to find it. Students present their findings to the class.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>

</subsection>